data.title: Australian Open: Harriet Dart the only winner on dismal day for Britain as Johanna Konta and Kyle Edmund lose
data.meta_description: Johanna Konta and Kyle Edmund, two of Great Britain’s best performers at the Australian Open in recent years, have both fallen at the first hurdle of this year’s event. data.text:
For a while, it looked set to be the darkest day for British sport in Melbourne since Australia’s cricketers defeated England by an innings and 99 runs inside three days at the nearby MCG in 2006. And then the unheralded Harriet Dart, a qualifier ranked No 164 in the world, stepped up at 10.59pm to prevent a wipeout of all Britons participating on day two of the Australian Open.

This was still a woeful experience for British tennis supporters at Melbourne Park. The day began with the exit of Johanna Konta before the clock had struck noon, and Kyle Edmund, Katie Boulter and Cameron Norrie later followed. There was not even a set to cheer until Norrie claimed one at 8.33pm.
